Medea, to avenge J ason on Pelias, who had killed AEson under the conviction that the Argonauta never could return, persuaded the daughters of Pelias to kill him and cut him in pieces, under pretence that she could boil him in her magio cauldron into renewed youth and beauty. For this, however, Medea and her husband were banished by the citizens of Iolcos, and took refuge in Corinth. Another version of the legend represents AEson as still alive when the Argonauts returned, and describes him as restored to youth by Medea. So Shakspeare‚ Merchant of Venice, Act v. scene 1.
